content.text:
## Design — Section 3: Authorization gate + role pinning

In `handler.ts`'s `build()`, capture the Google provider's parsed allowed-domains once (it's already in the `providers` array the function receives), then gate at user-creation time:

```ts
// parsed once per build: comma-separated → lowercased bare domains, [] when empty
const googleAllowedDomains = parseDomains(providers.find(p => p.kind === 'google')?.allowedDomains);

databaseHooks: {
  user: {
    create: {
      before: async (user) => {
        const domain = emailDomain(user.email);            // part after the last '@', lowercased
        if (googleAllowedDomains.length > 0 && !googleAllowedDomains.includes(domain)) {
          throw new APIError('FORBIDDEN', { message: 'email domain not permitted' });
        }
        return { data: { ...user, role: 'user' } };         // pin role — Google never grants admin
      },
    },
  },
}
```

Decisions baked in:
- **Empty `allowed_domains` ⇒ open** (matches your chosen policy + the optional UI field).
- **Gate fires only on user *creation*.** An already-provisioned user keeps access even if domains later tighten — gating is at provision time (consistent with the "no existing user" framing). I'll note this explicitly in the spec.
- **`role: 'user'` is forced**, never trusted from better-auth/provider input (I5). Only `auth:create-bootstrap-user` mints admins.
- **`exactOptionalPropertyTypes`** is on in this repo, so `parseDomains` handles the `undefined`/`null` provider cleanly.

Subtlety I'll verify in implementation: the exact `APIError` import/shape better-auth expects from a `before` hook so the throw becomes a clean callback-error redirect (not a 500). The test will pin this.

## Design — Section 4: The cookie bridge

This is the one genuinely fiddly part. better-auth creates the session row (now in `auth_better_v1_sessions`) but sets its *own* cookie (`better-auth.session_token`, better-auth-signed). `requireUser` reads `ax_auth_session` (http-server HMAC-signed). We bridge with `AsyncLocalStorage` so we never parse better-auth's cookie format:

```ts
// shared module within @ax/auth-better (not cross-plugin)
export const sessionTokenALS = new AsyncLocalStorage<{ token?: string }>();

// handler.ts databaseHooks:
session: { create: { after: async (session) => {
  const box = sessionTokenALS.getStore();
  if (box) box.token = session.token;     // raw token = the auth_better_v1_sessions.token
}}}
```

```ts
// plugin.ts forwardToBetterAuth — wrap the better-auth invocation:
const box: { token?: string } = {};
const webResponse = await sessionTokenALS.run(box, () => handle.current()(new Request(url, init)));
// …copy status/headers as today, BUT:
//   - filter out any Set-Cookie whose name is better-auth's session cookie
//   - if box.token is set, additionally res.setSignedCookie('ax_auth_session', box.token, opts)
```

- ALS context propagates through better-auth's internal awaits, so `session.create.after` writes into the same `box` the request created — request-scoped, concurrency-safe.
- We **strip better-auth's session cookie** and **keep its other cookies** (e.g., the state-cookie *clearing* on the callback). Detection is by better-auth's session-cookie name, which I'll pin explicitly via better-auth's cookie config so it's deterministic (not guessed).
- `opts` for `ax_auth_session` mirror what bootstrap/`auth:complete-bootstrap-user` already use: `path:'/'`, `sameSite:'Lax'`, `secure` when `NODE_ENV==='production'`, `maxAge: sessionLifetimeSeconds`.
- This bridge also lights up email/password sign-in (out of scope to test, but it's the same seam — free correctness, no extra code).

Do Sections 3 (gate) and 4 (cookie bridge) look right? Next I'll cover error handling/edge cases, testing, and the security review.
